const summary = "'`Dataset ds001_prostate contained ${n} patients and ${features.length} de-identified features plus the binary outcome objective_response. Overall response was ${fmtPct(results.overall.rate)} (${results.overall.events}/${n}). I analyzed main effects with response-rate differences, then fitted an all-feature linear probability model and followed up with subgroup and interaction tests on the strongest signals.'"\\n\\nThe dominant positive signal was feature_005. Objective response was "'${fmtPct(results.feature_005.A.rate)} with feature_005=1 versus ${fmtPct(results.feature_005.B.rate)} with feature_005=0, a +${fmt(results.feature_005.effect, 4)} response-rate difference (p=${fmtP(results.feature_005.p)}). The main negative binary signals were feature_034 (risk difference ${fmt(results.feature_034.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_034.p)}), feature_009 (${fmt(results.feature_009.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_009.p)}), feature_065 (${fmt(results.feature_065.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_065.p)}), and feature_055 (${fmt(results.feature_055.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_055.p)}). These effects remained directionally consistent in the all-feature adjusted model; adjusted response-scale coefficients were ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_005.effect, 4)} for feature_005, ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_034.effect, 4)} for feature_034, ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_009.effect, 4)} for feature_009, and ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_065.effect, 4)} for feature_065.'"\\n\\nSeveral non-binary features also showed response gradients. High feature_003 was adverse: above-median feature_003 had response "'${fmtPct(results.f003Med.A.rate)} versus ${fmtPct(results.f003Med.B.rate)} at or below median, risk difference ${fmt(results.f003Med.effect, 4)} (p=${fmtP(results.f003Med.p)}). Feature_023 showed a monotone decline from ${fmtPct(results.f023_levels[0].rate)} at level 0 to ${fmtPct(results.f023_levels[1].rate)} at level 1 and ${fmtPct(results.f023_levels[2].rate)} at level 2; level 2 versus 0 had risk difference ${fmt(results.f023_2v0.effect, 4)}. High feature_063 and feature_054 were adverse, with upper-quartile risk differences ${fmt(results.f063Q3.effect, 4)} and ${fmt(results.f054Q3.effect, 4).trim()}, respectively. Feature_027 was a smaller favorable signal: upper-quartile risk difference ${fmt(results.f027Q3.effect, 4)} (p=${fmtP(results.f027Q3.p)}).'"\\n\\nThe main clinical pattern was heterogeneity of the feature_005 association. Feature_005 was strongly favorable only in marker-negative strata. Its risk difference was "'${fmt(results.f005_by_034.cells['"'01'].rate - results.f005_by_034.cells['00'].rate, 4)} when feature_034=0 but only "'${fmt(results.f005_by_034.cells['"'11'].rate - results.f005_by_034.cells['10'].rate, 4)} when feature_034=1 (interaction "'${fmt(results.f005_by_034.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.f005_by_034.p)}). Analogous attenuation occurred for feature_009 (interaction ${fmt(results.f005_by_009.effect, 4)}), feature_065 (${fmt(results.f005_by_065.effect, 4)}), and feature_055 (${fmt(results.f005_by_055.effect, 4)}). When feature_034, feature_009, feature_065, and feature_055 were all absent, feature_005=1 had response ${fmtPct(results.f005_absent_neg.A.rate)} versus ${fmtPct(results.f005_absent_neg.B.rate)} for feature_005=0, a ${fmt(results.f005_absent_neg.effect, 4)} difference. When any of those four markers was present, the feature_005 difference shrank to ${fmt(results.f005_any_neg.effect, 4)} and was not significant at 0.05 (p=${fmtP(results.f005_any_neg.p)}).'"\\n\\nA compact high-response subgroup emerged: feature_005=1, all four negative binary markers absent, and feature_003 at or below the median. This subgroup had response "'${fmtPct(results.highRule.A.rate)} compared with ${fmtPct(results.highRule.B.rate)} for all other patients (risk difference ${fmt(results.highRule.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.highRule.p)}). Among feature_005=1 patients, any of the four negative markers reduced response from ${fmtPct(results.burden_f0051_any_vs_none.B.rate)} to ${fmtPct(results.burden_f0051_any_vs_none.A.rate)} (risk difference ${fmt(results.burden_f0051_any_vs_none.effect, 4)}). High feature_003 also attenuated the feature_005 effect: +${fmt(results.f005_by_f003_high.effectOut.effect, 4)} at/below median versus +${fmt(results.f005_by_f003_high.effectIn.effect, 4)} above median.'"\\n\\nThe negative binary markers also overlapped with one another rather than combining additively on the response-rate scale. Difference-in-differences were positive for feature_034 x feature_009 ("'${fmt(results.overlap_034_009.effect, 4)}), feature_034 x feature_065 (${fmt(results.overlap_034_065.effect, 4)}), and feature_009 x feature_065 (${fmt(results.overlap_009_065.effect, 4)}), all significant. As a negative-control style probe, feature_039 above the median was not meaningfully associated with response (risk difference ${fmt(results.f039Med.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.f039Med.p)}).'"\\n\\nOverall, the data support a strong treatment-biomarker-style structure: feature_005 marks a high-response subgroup, but this favorable association is largely conditional on absence of feature_034, feature_009, feature_065, and feature_055 and is attenuated by higher feature_003. Feature_023, feature_063, and feature_054 contribute additional adverse gradients, while feature_027 is a weaker favorable correlate."'`;

