+const summary = `Dataset ds001_prostate contained ${n} patients and ${features.length} de-identified features plus the binary outcome objective_response. Overall response was ${fmtPct(results.overall.rate)} (${results.overall.events}/${n}). I analyzed main effects with response-rate differences, then fitted an all-feature linear probability model and followed up with subgroup and interaction tests on the strongest signals.
+
+The dominant positive signal was feature_005. Objective response was ${fmtPct(results.feature_005.A.rate)} with feature_005=1 versus ${fmtPct(results.feature_005.B.rate)} with feature_005=0, a +${fmt(results.feature_005.effect, 4)} response-rate difference (p=${fmtP(results.feature_005.p)}). The main negative binary signals were feature_034 (risk difference ${fmt(results.feature_034.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_034.p)}), feature_009 (${fmt(results.feature_009.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_009.p)}), feature_065 (${fmt(results.feature_065.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_065.p)}), and feature_055 (${fmt(results.feature_055.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.feature_055.p)}). These effects remained directionally consistent in the all-feature adjusted model; adjusted response-scale coefficients were ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_005.effect, 4)} for feature_005, ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_034.effect, 4)} for feature_034, ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_009.effect, 4)} for feature_009, and ${fmt(results.adjusted.feature_065.effect, 4)} for feature_065.
+
+Several non-binary features also showed response gradients. High feature_003 was adverse: above-median feature_003 had response ${fmtPct(results.f003Med.A.rate)} versus ${fmtPct(results.f003Med.B.rate)} at or below median, risk difference ${fmt(results.f003Med.effect, 4)} (p=${fmtP(results.f003Med.p)}). Feature_023 showed a monotone decline from ${fmtPct(results.f023_levels[0].rate)} at level 0 to ${fmtPct(results.f023_levels[1].rate)} at level 1 and ${fmtPct(results.f023_levels[2].rate)} at level 2; level 2 versus 0 had risk difference ${fmt(results.f023_2v0.effect, 4)}. High feature_063 and feature_054 were adverse, with upper-quartile risk differences ${fmt(results.f063Q3.effect, 4)} and ${fmt(results.f054Q3.effect, 4)}, respectively. Feature_027 was a smaller favorable signal: upper-quartile risk difference ${fmt(results.f027Q3.effect, 4)} (p=${fmtP(results.f027Q3.p)}).
+
+The main clinical pattern was heterogeneity of the feature_005 association. Feature_005 was strongly favorable only in marker-negative strata. Its risk difference was ${fmt(results.f005_by_034.cells['01'].rate - results.f005_by_034.cells['00'].rate, 4)} when feature_034=0 but only ${fmt(results.f005_by_034.cells['11'].rate - results.f005_by_034.cells['10'].rate, 4)} when feature_034=1 (interaction ${fmt(results.f005_by_034.effect, 4)}, p=${fmtP(results.f005_by_034.p)}). Analogous attenuation occurred for feature_009 (interaction ${fmt(results.f005_by_009.effect, 4)}), feature_065 (${fmt(results.f005_by_065.effect, 4)}), and feature_055 (${fmt(results.f005_by_055.effect, 4)}). When feature_034, feature_009, feature_065, and feature_055 were all absent, feature_005=1 had response ${fmtPct(results.f005_absent_neg.A.rate)} versus ${fmtPct(results.f005_absent_neg.B.rate)} for feature_005=0, a ${fmt(results.f005_absent_neg.effect, 4)} difference. When any of those four markers was present, the feature_005 difference shrank to ${fmt(results.f005_any_neg.effect, 4)} and was not significant at 0.05 (p=${fmtP(results.f005_any_neg.p)}).
+
